<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHAT MANNER OF MAN IS THIS?; 
</P>
<P>
HUSSEIN'S FORCED TV SHOW WITH HIS 'GUESTS' WON'T HELP THE CAUSE OF PEACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein made an unexpected television appearance 
Thursday that may make a peaceful resolution of the military buildup in the 
Persian Gulf even more problematic. 
</P>
<P>
Iraqi authorities released videotape of a forced meeting between Saddam Hussein 
and a group of obviously uncomfortable Western hostages. No doubt the Iraqi 
president's aim in staging this unprecedented media event was to appear to 
Arabs as a reasonable man who wishes only to move back from war and who is 
deeply concerned about the hostages as human beings. He also wants to impress 
on the United States and the West that a full-scale air attack on key Iraqi 
installations will cause fearsome casualties among the thousands of Americans 
and other foreigners being held at many, if not all, of those installations in 
Iraq and Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
Governments in the West reacted to the appalling footage with predictable but 
nonetheless sincere and justifiable outrage. No one watching the videotape 
could fail to be moved by the thoroughly helpless plight of the men, women and 
children forced to be in that room with the Iraqi dictator. At one point in 
this bizarre and reprehensible performance, the camera moved its lens to a 
teen-age boy but quickly shifted away as tears welled up in his eyes. 
</P>
<P>
It risks tarnishing the point to suggest that the Iraqi president will require 
better advice on how to use mass media if he is to project a more positive 
image in the days and weeks ahead. A repeat of a performance like Thursday's 
will probably only serve to inflame Western opinion all the more against him. 
</P>
<P>
It was irritating to hear yet again that the Iraqi president regards these 
people, so trapped in the winds of war, not as hostages but as "guests." This 
cockeyed version of hospitality is insufferably infuriating, and it doesn't get 
more palatable with repetition. There can be no further evidence, if any were 
needed, that the Iraqis are enveloped in a war psychosis that is devoid of all 
reality. 
</P>
<P>
This is a dangerous business. It is always better for peace to prevail over 
war. If there is a diplomatic way out, that is the preferable route to take. 
But every day that option seems less likely, less realistic, more remote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Hussein and hostage on TV Thursday CNN 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
