<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLLS FINDS GLOOM OVER ECONOMY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pessimism about the economy has reached a level unseen since the early 1980s, 
when the United States fell into the worst recession since World War II, 
according to a New York Times-CBS News poll published today. 
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of Americans believe the country is already in a recession, the 
poll found. 
</P>
<P>
About 55% of respondents said they believe the economy is worsening, while 40% 
said it is staying the same and 4% said it is improving. 
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted in telephone interviews with 1,422 Americans from Aug. 
16 to Aug. 19. The margin of error was plus or minus three percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
