<HEADLINE>
<P>
POSTAL SERVICE FORMALLY OPENS CONTRACT TALKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Postal officials and union leaders today formally opened what will likely be 
months of grueling contract talks. 
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the parties will communicate together and work together to gain a 
contract marked by fairness and flexibility," Postmaster General Anthony M. 
Frank said. 
</P>
<P>
The financially strapped Postal Service is preaching moderation, meaning it 
hopes that workers will hold down their financial demands. 
</P>
<P>
But union leaders say their members should not suffer because of management's 
inability to improve efficiency and hold down costs. 
</P>
<P>
"We don't want the public to be gouged, but we're not going to take the blame 
for poor management either," said Moe Biller, president of the American Postal 
Workers Union. 
</P>
<P>
Labor contracts between the U.S. Postal Service and its four largest unions 
expire Nov. 20. The labor groups represent 660,000 workers. 
</P>
