<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
NOTE FROM GIRL TOUCHES DOUGLAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COLUMBUS, Ohio 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Heavyweight boxing champion James (Buster) Douglas says he was so moved by a 
note from a homeless girl that he sought her out and paid her a surprise visit 
at school. 
</P>
<P>
"It's something that keeps me in tune to how fortunate I am and the blessings 
that I can pass along to someone else," Douglas said of his meeting with 
12-year-old Paula Taylor. 
</P>
<P>
While Douglas was visiting the Columbus Boys' Club in late May, Paula had a 
handwritten note delivered to him. It asked Douglas to visit the Faith Mission, 
where homeless people stay. 
</P>
<P>
"She said that she was homeless and how much she loved me," Douglas said. "She 
invited me to come down to the shelter to show people that I do care about 
them." 
</P>
<P>
Douglas visited the shelter twice, hoping to meet the girl and her family. But 
they had already found a home. So he tracked her down and paid her a surprise 
visit at school. 
</P>
<P>
"It was amazing," Paula said."When I would see him on the news, I would never 
think in my life that I would ever meet him." 
</P>
<P>
Douglas has tried to help Paula's mother find a job and has bought gifts for 
the family and clothing for the girl. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Buster Douglas Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
